    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-02-17T05:13:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-02-17T05:13:00-05:00" n="71"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d71">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 861.00/1110</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Vladivostok</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_CJK1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Caldwell</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Vladivostok</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-02-17T19:00:00+08:47">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 17, 1918, 7 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received February 17, 5.45 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Peking requests I transmit copy of the following telegram sent Legation by Major
                        <persName corresp="#p_DLCWS1">Drysdale</persName>: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>February 15, 2 p.m. Probable German agents inciting Bolsheviks and labor
                            organizations and for purchase supplies for Germans. Prisoners of war
                            being released. Their organization possible menace <pb facs="0138"
                                n="48" xml:id="pg_48"/> Allied interests. Advise financial
                            assistance to organization of Zabaikal Cossacks under <persName
                                corresp="#p_SGG1">Semenov</persName> and Ussuri Cossacks under
                            Mendrin [Kalmykov?] as railway guard with <persName corresp="#p_ULA1"
                                >Ustrugov</persName>
                            <note n="1" xml:id="d71fn1">
                                <persName corresp="#p_ULA1">L. A. Ustrugov</persName>, formerly
                                Assistant Minister of Ways of Communication under <persName
                                    corresp="#p_KAF1">Kerensky</persName>; Feb. 9, 1918, Minister of
                                Ways of Communication in the provisional Siberian government.</note>
                            as head. Necessary expenditures to be supervised. These forces if
                            assisted financially will have little difficulty in controlling zone of
                            railway from Vladivostok to Karymskaya thus insuring protection Allied
                            interests. American, British, and French Consuls Vladivostok and Harbin
                            all advise some such effort necessary. I can see no probability of
                            explanation [compromising] our interests by such a move and our
                            interests certainly would be protected thereby. If scheme of financial
                            assistance approved my return Harbin necessary immediately. Please
                            advise me United States Consulate at Vladivostok. <persName
                                corresp="#p_DLCWS1">Drysdale</persName>.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_CJK1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Caldwell</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
